# 1. (10 points) The simple data set kid.weights contains 
# information on the weights for
# children aged 0 to 144 months

# a. Make a side-by-side boxpl


k = data.frame(kid.weights)
attach(k)
age.yr = cut(age, seq(0,144,by=12), labels=0:11)
par(mfrow=c(1,1), bg="white", fg = "black")
boxplot( dataSet[,2] ~ age.yr,
         xlab="Age in years.", ylab="Weight in pounds.", 
         main="Weight broken down by age.", col = "green"
         )

# b. What kind of trends do you see?

# There is a postive linear correlation between the age and weight.
# From birth until the age of eight the median weight 
# by years old is increasing.
# From ages 10 to 11 the median weight decreases.
# There is increased variablility in ages 8-11

# c. Plot the age as the x and the weight as the y 
# with a different color for each gender.

## Setting genders to color values of blue and pink.
##=============================##
#dataSet[,4]
g = unclass(dataSet[,4])
g = replace(g, g==2, "lightblue")
g = replace(g, g==1, "lightpink")

##=============================##
#head(dataSet)
colors = c("lightpink","lightblue")
names= c("Female","Male")
a1 = dataSet[,1]
w1 = dataSet[,2]
plot( a1,w1, col = g, pch=19,  xlab="Age in Months", ylab="Weight", 
      main="Weight broken down by age.")
legend(3, 140, names, col=colors, fill = colors)

# 2. (8 points) The simple data set carbon contains carbon monoxide levels 
# at 3 different industrial sites. The data has two variables:
# a carbon monoxide reading, and a factor variable to keep track of the site.
# Create side-by-side boxplots of the monoxide levels for
# each site. Does there appear to be a difference? How so?

par(mfrow=c(1,1))
cd = carbon
#head(cd)
boxplot( cd[,1]~ cd[,2], horizontal=F, las = 1,
         xlab="Site", ylab="CO Level", 
         main="CO Levels",
         col = c("#009c60","#86b535","#248c30"),
         boxwex=0.3
)
abline(h = c(.11,.12,.13,.14),  lty = 2, col = "grey")
abline(v = c(1.5,2.5),  lty = 2, col = "grey")
stripchart(cd[,1]~ cd[,2], add=T, method="stack", las = 1,vertical=T,
           xlab="Site", ylab="CO Level", pch=8, col="#005f87")

# Site 2 appears to have larger levels of Carbon monoxide.
# Each site appears to be skewed to the right.

# c. For the variables birthweight and gestation make a scatter plot
#    using different plotting characters (pch) depending on the 
#    level of the factor smoke.

NewB=babies[,c(5,7,10,21)]
NewB1 = subset(NewB, (NewB[,4] != 9))

par(mfrow=c(1,1))
smoke=as.factor(NewB1[,4])

w=NewB1[,2] 
g=NewB1[,1]

plot(g,w,pch=unclass(smoke),  xlab="Gestation length in days."
     , ylab="Weight in ounces.", 
     main="Birthweight and Gestation depending on smoke status of Mother."
     , xlim=c(130,400))

legend("topleft", inset=0.05,c("Never","Smokes now","Smoked until Pregnancy"
                               ,"Used to smoke"),pch=1:4, cex=0.5
       , title="Mother's smoking status",text.font=4)

# d. Summarize gestation by the race graphically and numerically.
b = data.frame(b)
# mother's race 0-5=white 6=mex 7=black 8=asian 9=mixed 99=unknown

#Race 10 not specified?

raceColor = c("green","green","green","green","green","green","blue","purple"
              ,"lightblue","lightpink","red","black")
fillColor = c("green","blue","purple","lightblue","lightpink","red","black")
boxplot( b[,5]~ b[,9], ylim=c(150,400), col =raceColor, xlab="Race."
         , ylab="Gestation length in days.", 
         main="Gestation by the Race of mother.")

abline(v = c(0.5,1.5,2.5,3.5,4.5,5.5,6.5,7.5,8.5,9.5,10.5,11.5,12.5)
       ,  lty = 2, col = "grey")

legend("topleft", inset=0.02,c("White","Hispanic","African American"
                               ,"Asian","mixed","Unknown1", "Unknown2")
       ,fill=fillColor, cex=0.5
       , title="Race",text.font=4)

r = cor(b[,5], b[,9])
r
## [1] -0.0287458
c1 = cor.test(b[,5], b[,9])
c1

##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  b[, 5] and b[, 9]
## t = -1.0102, df = 1234, p-value = 0.3126

##  -0.08436969  0.02705668
## sample estimates:
##        cor 
## -0.0287458
# Since 'r' is less than zero (r < 0), there is a negative correlation.
# As the value of r approaches zero, the correlation becomes weaker. 
# This is because the slope of the line is closer to zero. 
# Thus there is no relationship between Race and Gestation length.
